i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: While riding the bike lane a white SUV started backing out of the driveway slowly. They stopped with the backend of the vehicle in the bike lane waiting for cars. I slowed down and the driver finally noticed me and pulled back in to let me by.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: The Young Street bridge over Hope Slough is narrow with no bike lane when heading north. The Lafarge gravel trucks use this crossing several times a day. Yesterday, when I was riding home, a gravel truck decided to pass me on the bridge at the same time as a car was on the bridge heading south. So there was a car heading south, a speeding gravel truck heading north, and me on my e-bike with a trailer heading north. This is not the first time I've experienced this on this bridge.

i_type: Fall
details: There is a single railway style rail embedded in the road, running the length of the dam in the Eastbound side about 1m from the road edge with is a concrete barrier about 1m high.  The conditions were rainy, so the groove in the rail was full of water, obscuring it.  I was moving to my right to make room for an oncoming car when my front wheel caught the rail and threw me into the barrier.

i_type: Fall
details: We were bicycling on a dirt road on the east side of the Coquihalla River and highway 5, following the BC trail route published on bikepacking.com. The dirt road ended and we were looking for a way to cross the river. We dismounted the bikes and scrambled down the boulders to the river when my friend slipped and dislocated her shoulder. She was unable to push or ride her bike after that and we had to get her a ride back to Hope to the hospital to have it reset. That ended our trip.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was stopped with 2 feet on the ground on my side of the road at an intersection awaiting an opportunity to safely cross. a car, driving on the intersecting road, oversteered in their left turn and entered the wrong side if the road where i was standing. i was pushed up onto the hood and then when the car stopped thrown to the pavement. got a bad case of the ouchies, a busted bike, and a ride in an ambulance

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: A car passed extremely close and cut me off .  I was on a fast road bike going down hill at traffic speed.  It scared me so bad I involuntarily screamed in the moment because It sent me off balance at high speed.  I shook for a half hour after.  I’m a mother of two young children and they were almost left motherless.  I’m not sure if the aggressive driver thought about a mom trying to meet the school bus on time.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: motorist failed to stop at stop sign, i engaged in evasive manuever and narrowly (12inches) avoided a broadside. motorist was an elderly woman.

i_type: Fall
details: Some large transport truck was speeding and passed 3/4 of a meter or less from me, I was startled and tried to turn away (sometimes these trucks are very long with 2 trailers, I couldnt tell how long it was going to be in that split second), hit the curb and fell off my bike.  Truck was going too fast to see any license plate.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details:
greenish-yellow smart car accelerated to pass me and once ahead applied the brakes until stopped to parallel park. i had to bail into the left lane to avoid hitting the now stopped smartcar. 

cut-off
brake check

i_type: Near collision with stationary object or vehicle
details: I was riding east on Victoria a few feet from the parked cars. A motorist opened their door and I evaded. I pedalled home and changed my underwear.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Another car passed dangerously close. I think it was an illegal pass in an intersection since they passed right as i was coming out of the intersection.  20 sec later i think someone yelled at me for biking on the road

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was following another cyclist south on Gary St. when a car turned left to enter a parking lot, striking the first cyclist.  She flipped over the left front of the car striking her head and left shoulder.  EMS were called and attended to the cyclist.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Traffic stopped suddenly due to construction temporarily blocking entrance parking garage. Locked back tire to avoid collision.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was cycling NB in the two-way bike lane on Garry. A driver exited the surface parking lot to turn left onto SB Garry without looking both ways. The driver pulled out directly in front of me and I had to slam on my brakes and step off the bike to avoid a collision. The driver noticed me after and was not apologetic.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was biking down Garry in the temporary bike lane set up. I was about to pass the parking lot just north of Graham when a vehicle turned left into the lot without checking the bike lane. I had to slam on my brakes.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was cycling at moderate speed at ~18km/h along the two-directional bike path. A city work truck was stopped in the lot waiting to pull out. I proceeded carefully at a decreased speed until the vehicle began to move as I was just 2-3 meters away from it. The conditions were snow and ice and I was lucky not to lose control, and just managed to move out of its way. The driver did not look left at any point, and only came to a stop in the bike lane as I was right in front of him.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Riding in right lane, typically reserved for busses, on westbound Portage Ave. Very slow moving at time becuase of busses stopping and going. I saw no point in passing, so just sat it out. Proceeded through intersection of Portage-Hargrave, a not in service bus proceeded to pass me incredibly close, effectively pushing me out of the lane, meaning when there was no room between NW curb at corner and bus. Had to abruptly halt with brakes and feet, while narrowly avoiding bus, cm's on my right.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: SUV ran red light while turning left.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Cars turning right must move across bike lane

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: no bikelane at the bridge

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Southbound cycling here is kind of insane. There is a bus priority lane that can either go straight or turn right. It is impossible to be in the crib lane and proceed straight.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: It's necessary to take the lane on this block as the road surface is uneven and there is not enough space for vehicles to pass. Yet frequently in the morning, if enough of the back-in parking spaces are empty, vehicles will still accelerate aggressively and pass cyclists by driving over the parking spots, then swerving back in front of them before the curb bump-out.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Hydro truck turned left, crossing the bike lane without looking. I crashed into the driver's door.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Car was rolling the stop sign to turn right from McDermot to SB Rorie at the same time that I came to the stop sign and was heading straight across the intersection on the McDermot bike lane. I yelled and they stopped turning and I crossed the intersection.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding in the roundabout when a truck entered and cut me off, narrowly missing me. The driver glared at me before continuing on.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle was signing right but decided to turn left. I was on the left hand side going past but noticed the driver looking around so was cautious. If I had not been aware I would have been hit.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Riding eastbound down McDermot, just before Rorie, in the protected bike lane, a car turning right into the parking garage almost hit me. They made the right turn without signalling or slowing down.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details:
Vehicle turning right did not yield to the bike lane and the green cycle light. Caused a right hook collision, knocking me to the ground.

I cycle through this intersection daily and these types of collisions and near-misses are extremely common, as vehicles are not looking for cyclists who have the right of way.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: The advanced cycling signal seems timed so that vehicles get the green to turn just as cyclists are entering the intersection. The driver turning right did not look before turning, and nearly hit me on my bike. Right hook near-misses happen frequently to me in all the exchange district lanes.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Driver merged into roundabout without proper check and almost drove me over.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was cycling through the roundabout when a vehicle entered too soon underestimating my speed, and nearly cut me off. She braked in time but if she hadn't I would have collided with the front driver side of the car.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details:
I was riding my bike through the construction zone on Ellice Avenue.  As the 
 construction zone was ending a white pickup truck slammed on the gas and nearly clipped me on the bike.  I was clearly visible and was riding on the right side of the lane.

I only ride on Ellice because the St. Matthews bike lane ends at Maryland.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding northbound in the Sherbrook bike lane when a taxi turning from a nearby backlane turned into the bike lane forcing me to stop suddenly to avoid a collision.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Street does not have appropriate bike infrastructure. Car passed at a high speed and within feet of hitting me. Either you take up a whole lane on your bike, and cars pass you angrily and dangerously, or you ride closer to curb or parked cars, and cars still pass dangerously and angrily.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details:
I was cycling along Sargentnon my way to work ( the date is approx), when a truck pulled up to lane way to drive out, then did not pause, simply drive out.  I yelled and was able to touch the truck on my right side and it’s right side it was that close.  
Driver did not look carefully or perhaps not at all.  I had the 100% right of way as I was on the Main Street and going straight there was no light. They were pulling out of a business lot.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was using the “Car Lane” to avoid the sand/potholes that were in the bike lane. Driver passed me closely and fast. We both caught the red light and I asked him why he passed me so closely and he said that I should be in the bike lane.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Going EB on McDermot bike lane just west of Sherbrook. SUV came from behind me and started turning right on to SB Sherbrook across my path. I had ROW; both bike and vehicle lights were green. I braked hard to a stop and yelled; they briefly stopped but then kept turning in front of me and I had to clear the intersection on yellow/red.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle turning right from McDermot onto SB Sherbrook almost hit me as I was proceeding straight through the intersection EB on McDermot. I had to brake quickly to avoid being hit. There is a sign at this intersection indicating that turning vehicles must yield to cyclists in the protected bike lane. I assume the driver did not shoulder check to see if there was a bicycle in the bike lane before proceeding.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle turning right, trying to make light. Didnt see me oncoming. Ive had multiple incidents on this street on my way to the university (work). Although there is a dedicated bike lane, it is a one way street and vehicles do not look both ways. Need to be very careful when approaching crossroads

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Large black Jeep was obstructing the bike lane while waiting for a pedestrian to cross before completing its right turn. I had ROW coming EB on bike lane on green light. Jeep did not see me and I would have collided with it had I not ceded to its turn.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Right-turning SUV was only looking left for EB cars, not right for WB cyclists or pedestrians. I would have been hit had I not come to a near stop until they finally saw me.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding in the roundabout trying to turn on the bike lane going down Bannatyne. A car pulled up behind me and narrowly avoided hitting me.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle turning right across a bike lane failed to shoulder check and almost hit two cyclists

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Biking in the dedicated bike lane approaching McDermot.  Multiple vehicles turned left without slowing down and yielding for me, including a city bus that had to stop, back up and turn again in order to clear the intersection.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding down the princess street protected lane. At McDermott an SUV turned left in front of me without slowing down when I was heading through the intersection. I had to stop but I had the right of way.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Cycling down Princess in bike lane and 2 vehicles turned left right before I was at the intersection.  I had to brake hard to avoid them.  They did not yield for me, or even look for me.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding westbound on a protected bike lane and a motorist turned right in front of me just as I entered the intersection (light was still green for several seconds longer). He was still looking leftward for motorists and not at all aware of cyclists going straight through (the protected bike lane is fairly new).  Luckily I hammered on the brakes in time and swerved sideways but didn't slide under his vehicle. Meantime he was still looking left for motorists till he heard me yell Whoah!

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicles were not yielding to me when they were approaching the corner to turn right.  I had to brake hard to avoid getting hit.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle turned right through a bike lane and pedestrian corridor when they had green and vehicle light was red. Nearly struck two cyclists and one pedestrian.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: One SUV was stopped across the Bannatyne bike lane and sidewalk after entering the intersection when they couldn't clear it.  A second SUV then turned right in to the left-hand lane of King without signalling; had I not slowed for the first SUV I likely would have been hit by the second one. I had right of way going straight on a green light, and had checked for right turning vehicles, but they didn't signal.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was riding in the protected bike lane when a van turned right without signalling to cut through the parking lot of the Canada Post station to avoid having to wait for  the turn signal at the next intersection.  I watched the van proceed through the parking lot and then turn right.  I was forced to bake quickly and my bike slid out from underneath me due to the wet and slippery road condition.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle driver and passenger looking right when making a left turn.  Vehicle did not make a full stop at stop sign.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: New pathway alignment creates blind spot around Galt Street Station. Two cyclists nearly hit head-on. The older pathway needs to be realigned to tee into new route.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Truck crossing McDermot on Kate St passed through the McDermot bike lane wihout looking for cyclists. I was forced to brake to avoid t-boning the truck.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle passed me too close to the entrance to the roundabout and almost collided with me. I had to brake to avoid being side swiped

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: A no-right-on-red sign/condition for vehicles is needed here. I have been nearly hit at least twice.  The green bike lead light may make it more dangerous, as cars are only looking left to Isabel for NB traffic, and that traffic will have had a red for a few seconds and therefore have stopped when the bike light goes green for WB travel.  Cars turning from WB to NB then start making the turn without regard for cyclists or pedestrians.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: A minivan turned onto McDermot without seeing me/looking for cyclists or pedestrians, although I had lights and my bike is bright white and red. I was T-boned, and my body went flying over the hood of the vehicle and onto the roof. The incident resulted in somewhat minor but persistent knee and back injuries that still affect me today, and my bike was nearly totalled. The frame was salvaged but required new wheels (the old ones had been bent almost in half by the impact), handlebar, fork etc..

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Turning left (South) onto Lily, heading west bound on Galt. Fast moving cars flowing off of Disraeli Freeway. This happens regularly, once every few months. I know its an issue, but it still surprises me how quickly cars come flying into the neighbourhood.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Minivan approaching from left ran a red.   As a rule I do not jump reds and will wait until  I have green for at least a second.  Another motorist stopped in the lane beside the runner had the foresight to use horn which made me that much more aware that a vehicle was approaching and going through the lights illegally.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Southbound bike lane ends before the intersection at Higgens. Dump truck cut me off to turn right then slammed on brakes to wait for traffic in front, blocking all lanes. Had to go all the way around left side of vehicle to get through intersection. This was not a unique incident for me here. Probably happens every week or two. There should be a safer way for cyclists to get to the bike path on the other side of Higgens.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was cycling northbound on Waterfront after the roundabout, approaching the intersection at Higgins and Waterfront. I had stopped pedalling but had not yet started applying the brakes when I was thrown from my bike when a driver hit me from behind. He stopped and started to blame me for slowing down, but soon relented knowing he was wrong.  I had TWO rear lights AND a cycling-specific reflective jacket on, so there's no way he "didn't see" me unless he was looking at his phone.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle heading EB on McDermot and turning right onto SB Olivia turned right across the bike lane directly in front of me, forcing me to brake hard and swerve to avoid hitting them. I was traveling WB on McDermot, so there was no issue with sight-lines as I was approaching the vehicle from the front. The low sun rising in the east might have impaired their vision, though they seemed distracted trying to figure out where they were trying to go and didn't seem to look for bicycles.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle turning right onto McDermot from Pearl pulled out across the bike lane as I was approaching. Driver was focused on vehicle traffic coming from the left and failed to look right to check the two-way bike lane before pulling out from the stop sign. I had to slam on my brakes to avoid a collision. This is a frequent occurrence at this intersection. Drivers need to pay attention and look both directions.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle heading NB on Pearl and turning right onto EB McDermot pulled out directly in front of me, forcing me to slam on my brakes and come to a full stop to avoid a collision. The driver of the vehicle was looking to their left for approaching traffic, but did not look to their right for approaching bicycles in the two-way bike lane before pulling forward from the stop sign. The driver just shrugged when they eventually saw me after I had come to a complete stop in the bike lane.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle traveling EB on McDermot turned right onto Pearl without looking for cyclists in the two-way bike lane (despite a sign at that intersection indicating that right-turning vehicles must yield to bicycles in the bike lane). I was traveling WB in the bicycle lane and had to slam on my brakes to avoid hitting the car as it turned in front of me. I came to a complete stop just beside the driver's window. The driver seemed surprised that I was there and waved a hand apologetically.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle and myself both stopped at the corner to let a pedestrian pass by but before stopping I already noted that the vehicle didn't flash any signal light so I assumed he was going straight.  When it was time to go we went at the same time, I went straight and the deriver suddenly turned right and so I got hit and fell to the ground.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: SUV joining from side street (Pearl St) , waited for another vehicle travelling from the opposite direction on McDermott Ave but completely missed me wearing a fluorescent top on a bright day. Factor was that vehicular traffic is one way only on McDermott but the bike lane is both ways.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I was crossing Notre Dame SB on east side of Arlington. NB SUV turning right turned between the pedestrians crossing north and myself, when he should have waited for the crosswalk to be clear. I made a "what are you doing" hands up gesture; driver appeared to then be yelling at me, though their window was up. Aso, the SE corner of this intersection leaves little room for pedestrians/cyclists to wait as a pole is placed in it.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle leaving the parking lot was only looking to its left for EB cars, and was obstructing the sidewalk and EB bike lane while it waited to turn. I waited until they saw me before crossing WB in front of it, otherwise I would likely have been hit. I waived at the driver and they seemed apologetic.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle
details: A vehicle coming out of the parking lot to merge with the street was waiting right on the bike lane blocking the line of sight of both oncoming cyclists from either direction.  The bike lane is two-way, I stayed on my lane heading east and cannot see that there was an oncoming cyclist who didn't see me as well.  The other cyclist swerved to my lane (at the back of the car) just right when the car was to go, then we (cyclists) both collided.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Motorcycle almost hit me while passing me under the bridge. He literally hunk at me for being on the right side lane, then passed me a foot away. I was on the middle of the lane as it's my right.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: There are marked crosswalks across both Midwinter and Talbot for a total of 4 lanes in close proximity.  Motorists are going through both crosswalks every single day.  Do not cross unless the cars come to a complete stop or no cars are approaching and then do not hesitate.  Once counted 12 cars blow by before I was allowed to cross.  If I wanted to create a dangerous situation for pedestrians this is how I would have built it.  A fatality waiting to happen.

i_type: Collision with stationary object or vehicle

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Fall

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

A semi-tractor truck passed me probably less than 4 inches from my handlebars. Midway through passing me I was sucked in toward the trailer due to the air pocket from the passing trailer. A less  proficient cyclist would have been run over. Truck going to Border Chemical

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

Then saw me just as the vehicle was entering the left lane and slammed the brakes and jolted the steering wheel. Managed to wave an apology.

i_type: Collision with moving object or vehicle

He got out and pushed me down, while I was still on my bike.  He kicked at me and continued to say things about cyclists.  I managed to get untangled from the bike.  When I was putting my chain back on, he pulled me back into the intersection by the hood on my sweater.  A car then accidently ran over my bike.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details:

They slammed on their brakes to stop at the stop sign, but then accelerated wildly again, swerving at the last second to avoid me.

I stopped my bike and waved my arms to express my anger at their reckless driving. The man apologized profusely out his window at me - he said he didn't see me.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: Vehicle sped past; close pass only to brake and turn left.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
details: I ride McKercher Dr between 8th and Taylor Streets on my way to work. This stretch has very very light traffic, usually only a few cars, so I ride in middle of right lane leaving left lane wide open. Numerous times I have been tailed closely by a car with driver leaning on the horn, driver then guns engine and swerves past me in the empty left lane, then swerves in front of me, leaning on the horn the whole time. My heart races for the nxt several minutes. So unsettling. So unnecessary.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

He glared at me as he went by. I continued behind him and immediately caught up to him at the next red light.

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle

i_type: Near collision with moving object or vehicle
